295. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Ovid MEDLINE(R) <2017>
ID  - 28681949
T1  - Age-stratified thresholds of anti-Mullerian hormone improve prediction of polycystic ovary syndrome over a population-based threshold.
T3  - Comment in: Clin Endocrinol (Oxf). 2017 Dec;87(6):649-650 PMID: 28949024 [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/28949024]
DO  - https://dx.doi.org/10.1111/cen.13415
A1  - Quinn, Molly M
A1  - Kao, Chia-Ning
A1  - Ahmad, Asima K
A1  - Haisenleder, Daniel J
A1  - Santoro, Nanette
A1  - Eisenberg, Esther
A1  - Legro, Richard S
A1  - Cedars, Marcelle I
A1  - Huddleston, Heather G
A2  - NIH/NICHD Reproductive Medicine Network
Y1  - 2017//
Y2  - 20170804//
N1  - Comment in (CIN)
N2  - OBJECTIVE: Due to its consistent elevation in polycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS) and correlation with polycystic ovarian morphology (PCOM), anti-Mullerian hormone (AMH) has been proposed as a marker of the syndrome. However, prior studies reporting thresholds of AMH for a PCOS diagnosis have been limited by small sample size, inappropriate controls, and heterogeneous AMH assays. We sought to evaluate the suitability of a standardized AMH assay as a biomarker of PCOS., DESIGN: Cross-sectional study at academic medical centres across the United States., PATIENTS: Women with PCOS were diagnosed by Rotterdam criteria and included 282 subjects from the multisite PPCOS II trial and 109 patients from a tertiary academic centre's multidisciplinary PCOS clinic. Controls included 245 participants in the ovarian ageing (OVA) study, a community-based cohort of ovulatory women not seeking treatment for fertility., MEASUREMENTS: Determination of AMH by a central laboratory. Receiver-operating characteristic (ROC) analyses were used to investigate the accuracy of AMH thresholds for prediction of PCOS diagnosis with stratification by age., RESULTS: The optimal threshold of AMH to distinguish PCOS from controls was 55.36 pmol/L (sensitivity: 0.82, specificity: 0.78, J: 0.60). When examining the population by age groups, the optimal AMH threshold decreased with increasing age., CONCLUSIONS: AMH is an effective biomarker of PCOS. Age-stratified thresholds more accurately predicted PCOS than an overall population-based threshold. Copyright © 2017 John Wiley & Sons Ltd.
