325. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Ovid MEDLINE(R) PubMed-not-MEDLINE <2017 to 2019>
ID  - 31181872
T1  - Clinical application of serum anti-Mullerian hormone in women.
DO  - https://dx.doi.org/10.5653/cerm.2019.46.2.50
A1  - Oh, So Ra
A1  - Choe, Sun Yi
A1  - Cho, Yeon Jean
Y1  - 2019//
Y2  - 20190601//
N2  - Anti-Mullerian hormone (AMH), a peptide growth factor of the transforming growth factor-beta family, is a reliable marker of ovarian reserve. Regarding assisted reproductive technology, AMH has been efficiently used as a marker to predict ovarian response to stimulation. The clinical use of AMH has recently been extended and emphasized. The uses of AMH as a predictive marker of menopause onset, diagnostic tool for polycystic ovary syndrome, and assessment of ovarian function before and after gynecologic surgeries or gonadotoxic agents such as chemotherapy have been investigated. Serum AMH levels can also be affected by environmental and genetic factors; thus, the effects of factors that may alter AMH test results should be considered. This review summarizes the findings of recent studies focusing on the clinical application of AMH and factors that influence the AMH level and opinions on the use of the AMH level to assess the probability of conception before reproductive life planning as a "fertility test."
